Preheat your oven to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Remove the @21 Day Aged British Sirloin Steaks{2} from your fridge to allow them to come up to room temperature. Fill and boil your #kettle{}. Pour enough oil into a deep #baking tray{} to cover the bottom and pop into the oven. Peel and chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 3cm chunks. Pour the boiling water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Boil the potatoes for ~{7-8%minutes} or until the edges are soft.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2}(peeled) (or use a #garlic press{}). Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then finely chop. Halve any thick @Purple Sprouting Broccoli{150%g} stems lengthways then pop them onto a baking tray. Drizzle with oil, scatter over the garlic and chilli (careful, it's hot - use less if you don't like too much heat), then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out in a single layer and set aside.

Once the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{} and sprinkle on the @plain flour{8%tbsp}. Shake to fluff up the potatoes, then carefully add them to the hot baking tray, turning in the oil. Season with salt then roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{30-35%minutes}. Turn halfway through.

When the potatoes have about ~{15%minutes} cooking time left, pop the broccoli onto the middle shelf to roast for the remaining cooking time until tender and crispy, ~{10-15%minutes}. Once the broccoli is in the oven, heat a drizzle of oil in a large #frying pan{} on high heat. Season the steaks with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

When the oil is hot, lay the steaks into the pan and fry until browned, ~{1%minute} on each side. Lower the heat slightly and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} on each side if you want them medium-rare.

> TIP: Cook for 1-2 mins more if you like it more well done.

Once cooked, transfer to a #cutting board{}, cover with #foil{} and allow to rest.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. The steak is safe to eat when the outside is browned.

While the steaks rest, pop the (now empty) frying pan back on medium heat. Pour in the @water{250%ml} for the sauce and bring to the boil on high heat. Stir in the @red wine jus paste{1}, then reduce the heat to medium-high. Allow the sauce to bubble and thicken, stirring regularly, ~{5-6%minutes}. Once glossy and thickened, remove from the heat. Thinly slice the steaks widthways, then serve with the roast potatoes and broccoli alongside. Spoon over the red wine jus to finish. Enjoy!